The `==` operator in Java is used to compare primitive data types (like int, char, boolean) for identity. It checks if two variables point to the same memory location.

However, when it comes to comparing strings, you should use the `.equals()` method instead. The `.equals()` method compares the content of two strings for equality. It checks if the two strings have the same sequence of characters.

Here's why you encountered a bug when using `==` for strings: In Java, strings are immutable. When you assign a value to a string variable, a new string object is created in the memory with that value. If you assign two string literals using the `=` operator, both variables point to the same string object in the string pool. But if you assign strings using new keyword or string concatenation, each variable points to a different string object.

So, if you compare two string variables using `==` operator, it checks if they point to the same memory location, which is not what you want when comparing strings. Instead, use the `.equals()` method to compare the content of two strings.

Here's an example:

```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";

if (str1 == str2) { // This will be false
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are the same object");
}

if (str1.equals(str2)) { // This will be true
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 have the same content");
}
```

In summary, use `==` for comparing primitive data types and `.equals()` for comparing strings.

